    researcher: 'Leon Festinger',
    what_it_is: 'Deindividuation is a state of decreased self-awareness and weakened personal responsibility that can occur when individuals are part of a large crowd or wear disguises. In these situations, people feel anonymous, believing they cannot be singled out for their actions. This psychological shift reduces the activity of the prefrontal cortex, which monitors personal morals and social consequences. Consequently, individuals default to group behaviors, often participating in aggressive, emotional, or irrational acts they would never perform alone, as their personal moral compass is temporarily replaced by the collective mood of the crowd. This shift in identity explains why crowds can engage in extreme behaviors that individual members would find shocking.',
    real_scenario: 'Consider Sanjay, a mild-mannered college student in Chennai who has never raised his voice in public. One evening, he joins a massive protest march in the city center. As the crowd gets angry and starts shouting slogans, Sanjay feels his individuality melt away. Wrapped in the anonymity of the crowd, he begins screaming loudly and pushing barricades, acting with an aggression that completely shocks him when he returns home alone. The anonymity of the massive crowd allowed Sanjay to scream and push, shedding his usual mild-mannered personality.',
    why_it_evolved: 'In ancestral times, coordinate group action was essential for defense and warfare. A warrior who remained too self-aware and concerned with personal safety would hesitate during battle, risking the group\'s defeat. Deindividuation allowed individuals to merge into a single, cohesive unit, acting with collective force and courage to protect the tribe against external threats.',
    what_to_notice: 'Notice how your behavior changes when you wear a mask, a uniform, or join a large crowd. Stay aware of your personal values, ensuring you do not let anonymity dictate your actions. Notice how your sense of personal responsibility changes when you wear a uniform or join a march.',
    closing_thought: 'A crowd provides a mask that can hide us from our own conscience.'
